<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics" title=3D"Mathem=
atics">mathematics</a>, <b>exponentiation</b>, denoted <span class=3D"texht=
ml"><i>b</i><sup><i>n</i></sup></span>, is an <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Operation_(mathematics)" title=3D"Operation (mathematics)">oper=
ation</a> involving two numbers: the <i>base</i>, <span class=3D"texhtml mv=
ar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span>, and the <i>exponent</i> or <i>po=
wer</i>, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:1_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation#cite_note-:1-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> When <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> is a positive <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integer" title=3D"Integer">integer</a>,=
 exponentiation corresponds to repeated <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Multiplication" title=3D"Multiplication">multiplication</a> of the ba=
se: that is, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i><sup><i>n</i></sup></span> is =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Product_(mathematics)" title=
=3D"Product (mathematics)">product</a> of multiplying <span class=3D"texhtm=
l mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> bases:<sup id=3D"cite_ref-:1_=
1-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponenti=
ation#cite_note-:1-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle b^{n}=3D\underbrace {b\times b\times \dots \times b\times b} _{=
n{\text{ times}}}.}">
  <semantics>
