er/svg/f11423fbb2e967f986e36804a8ae4271734917c3" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:0.998ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle b}"=
></span> and any real number exponent <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-m=
ath-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a=
11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/Ma=
thML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle x}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>x</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle x}</annotatio=
n>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/87f9e315fd7e2ba406057a97300593c4802b53e4" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:1.33ex; height:1.676ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle x}">=
</span>. More involved definitions allow <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Complex_numbers" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Complex numbers">com=
plex</a> base and exponent, as well as certain types of <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_(mathematics)" title=3D"Matrix (mathematics)">=
matrices</a> as base or exponent.
</p><p>Exponentiation is used extensively in many fields, including <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Economics" title=3D"Economics">economics<=
/a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biology" title=3D"Biology">bi=
ology</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chemistry" title=3D"Che=
mistry">chemistry</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Physics" ti=
tle=3D"Physics">physics</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C=
omputer_science" title=3D"Computer science">computer science</a>, with appl=
ications such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Compound_interest=
" title=3D"Compound interest">compound interest</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Population_growth" title=3D"Population growth">populatio=
n growth</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chemical_reaction_ki=
netics" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Chemical reaction kinetics">chemical=
 reaction kinetics</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wave" titl=
e=3D"Wave">wave</a> behavior, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Public-key_cryptography" title=3D"Public-key cryptography">public-key crypt=
ography</a>.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Etymology">Etymology</h2><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DExponentiation&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Etymology"><span>edi=
t</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The term <i>exponent</i> originates from the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Latin" title=3D"Latin">Latin</a> <i>exponentem</i>, the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Present_participle" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Present participle">present participle</a> of <i>exponere</i>, =
meaning "to put forth".<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation#cite_note-4"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
The term <i>power</i> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Latin_langu=
age" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Latin language">Latin</a>: <i lang=3D"l=
a">potentia, potestas, dignitas</i>) is a mistranslation<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-Rotman_5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E=
xponentiation#cite_note-Rotman-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation#cite_no=
te-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_Gr=
eek" title=3D"Ancient Greek">ancient Greek</a> =CE=B4=CF=8D=CE=BD=CE=B1=CE=
=BC=CE=B9=CF=82 (<i>d=C3=BAnamis</i>, here: "amplification"<sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-Rotman_5-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Exponentiation#cite_note-Rotman-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>) used by the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greek_mathematics" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Greek mathematics">Greek</a> mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Euclid" title=3D"Euclid">Euclid</a> for the square of a line,<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-MacTutor_7-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation#cite_note-MacTutor-7"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> followin=
g <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hippocrates_of_Chios" title=3D"H=
ippocrates of Chios">Hippocrates of Chios</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation#cite=
_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The word <i>exponent</i> was coined in 1544 by Michael Stifel.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Exponentiation#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation#cite_note=
-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> In the 16th century, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Robert_Recorde" title=3D"Robert Recorde">Robert Recorde</a> used the ter=
ms "square", "cube", "zenzizenzic" (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Fourth_power" title=3D"Fourth power">fourth power</a>), "sursolid" (<a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fifth_power_(algebra)" title=3D"Fifth p=
ower (algebra)">fifth</a>), "zenzicube" (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Sixth_power" title=3D"Sixth power">sixth</a>), "second sursolid" (<a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seventh_power" title=3D"Seventh powe=
r">seventh</a>), and "<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zenzizenzize=
nzic" title=3D"Zenzizenzizenzic">zenzizenzizenzic</a>" (<a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eighth_power" title=3D"Eighth power">eighth</a>).<sup=
 id=3D"cite_ref-worldwidewords_11-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation#cite_note-worldwidewords-11"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> "Biquadrate" has been used to refer to the fourth power as well.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DExponentiation&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</spa=
n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Sand_Reckoner" title=
=3D"The Sand Reckoner">The Sand Reckoner</a></i>, <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Archimedes" title=3D"Archimedes">Archimedes</a> proved the =
law of exponents, <span class=3D"texhtml">10<sup><i>a</i></sup> =C2=B7 10<s=
up><i>b</i></sup> =3D 10<sup><i>a</i>+<i>b</i></sup></span>, necessary to m=
anipulate powers of <span class=3D"texhtml">10</span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1=
2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiat=
ion#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">]</span></a></sup> He then used powers of <span class=3D"texhtml=
">10</span> to estimate the number of grains of sand that can be contained =
in the universe.
</p><p>In the 9th century, the Persian mathematician <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Al-Khwarizmi" title=3D"Al-Khwarizmi">Al-Khwarizmi</a> us=
ed the terms =D9=85=D9=8E=D8=A7=D9=84 (<i>m=C4=81l</i>, "possessions", "pro=
perty") for a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square_(algebra)" ti=
tle=3D"Square (algebra)">square</a>=E2=80=94the Muslims, "like most mathema=
ticians of those and earlier times, thought of a squared number as a depict=
ion of an area, especially of land, hence property"<sup id=3D"cite_ref-worl=
dwidewords_11-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Exponentiation#cite_note-worldwidewords-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=E2=80=94and =D9=
=83=D9=8E=D8=B9=D9=92=D8=A8=D9=8E=D8=A9 (<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Kaaba" title=3D"Kaaba">Ka=CA=BFbah</a></i>, "cube") for a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cube_(algebra)" title=3D"Cube (algebra)">=
cube</a>, which later <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematics_=
in_the_medieval_Islamic_world" title=3D"Mathematics in the medieval Islamic=
 world">Islamic</a> mathematicians represented in <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_notation" title=3D"Mathematical notation">math=
ematical notation</a> as the letters <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/M%C4%ABm" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"M=C4=ABm">m=C4=ABm</a></i> (=
m) and <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/K%C4%81f" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"K=C4=81f">k=C4=81f</a></i> (k), respectively, by the 15th =
century, as seen in the work of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ab=
u%27l-Hasan_ibn_Ali_al-Qalasadi" title=3D"Abu'l-Hasan ibn Ali al-Qalasadi">=
Abu'l-Hasan ibn Ali al-Qalasadi</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation#cite_note-13">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup>
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nicolas_Chuquet" title=3D"Nicolas =
Chuquet">Nicolas Chuquet</a> used a form of exponential notation in the 15t=
h century, for example <span class=3D"texhtml">12<sup>2</sup></span> to rep=
resent <span class=3D"texhtml">12<i>x</i><sup>2</sup></span>.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Expo=
nentiation#cite_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This was later used by <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henricus_Grammateus" title=3D"Henricus Grammateus=
">Henricus Grammateus</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mich=
ael_Stifel" title=3D"Michael Stifel">Michael Stifel</a> in the 16th century=
. In the late 16th century, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jost_B=
%C3%BCrgi" title=3D"Jost B=C3=BCrgi">Jost B=C3=BCrgi</a> would use Roman nu=
merals for exponents in a way similar to that of Chuquet, for example <span=
 class=3D"sfrac nowrap;"><span style=3D"display:none; display:inline-block;=
 text-align:center;"><span style=3D"display:block; line-height:0.8em; font-=
size:70%;">iii</span><span style=3D"display:block; line-height:1em;">4</spa=
n></span></span> for <span class=3D"texhtml">4<i>x</i><sup>3</sup></span>.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-cajori_15-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation#cite_note-cajori-15"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In 1636, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Hume_(mathem=
atician)" title=3D"James Hume (mathematician)">James Hume</a> used in essen=
ce modern notation, when in <i>L'alg=C3=A8bre de Vi=C3=A8te</i> he wrote <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml"><i>A</i><sup>iii</sup></span> for <span class=3D"texh=
tml"><i>A</i><sup>3</sup></span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation#cite_note-16"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> Early in the 17th century, the first form of our modern exponentia=
l notation was introduced by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ren%C=
3%A9_Descartes" title=3D"Ren=C3=A9 Descartes">Ren=C3=A9 Descartes</a> in hi=
s text titled <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/La_G%C3%A9om%C3%A=
9trie" title=3D"La G=C3=A9om=C3=A9trie">La G=C3=A9om=C3=A9trie</a></i>; the=
re, the notation is introduced in Book I.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation#cite_note=
-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup>
</p>
<blockquote class=3D"templatequote"><p>I designate ... <span class=3D"texht=
ml"><i>aa</i></span>, or <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sup>2</sup></span=
> in multiplying <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span> by itself; and <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i><sup>3</sup></span> in multiplying it once mor=
e again by <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>a</i></span>, and thus to infinity.</=
p></blockquote><div class=3D"templatequotecite"><p style=3D"display: inline=
; padding-left: 2.3em;">=E2=80=94=E2=80=8ARen=C3=A9 Descartes, <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/La_G%C3%A9om%C3%A9trie" title=3D"La G=C3=A9om=
=C3=A9trie">La G=C3=A9om=C3=A9trie</a><span style=3D"display:none" data-plu=
ral=3D"1"></span></p></div>
<p>Some mathematicians (such as Descartes) used exponents only for powers g=
reater than two, preferring to represent squares as repeated multiplication=
. Thus they would write <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial=
" title=3D"Polynomial">polynomials</a>, for example, as <span class=3D"texh=
tml"><i>ax</i> + <i>bxx</i> + <i>cx</i><sup>3</sup> + <i>d</i></span>.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samuel_Jeake" title=3D"Samu=
el Jeake">Samuel Jeake</a> introduced the term <i>indices</i> in 1696.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-MacTutor_7-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation#cite_note-MacTutor-7"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The term <i>=
involution</i> was used synonymously with the term <i>indices</i>, but had =
declined in usage<sup id=3D"cite_ref-18" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation#cite_note-18"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and sho=
uld not be confused with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Involutio=
n_(mathematics)" title=3D"Involution (mathematics)">its more common meaning=
</a>.
</p><p>
In 1748, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leonhard_Euler" title=3D"=
Leonhard Euler">Leonhard Euler</a> introduced variable exponents, and, impl=
icitly, non-integer exponents by writing:<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inlin=
e-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r1244412712"></p><blockquote class=
=3D"templatequote"><p>Consider exponentials or powers in which the exponent=
 itself is a variable. It is clear that quantities of this kind are not <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_function" title=3D"Algebrai=
c function">algebraic functions</a>, since in those the exponents must be c=
onstant.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Euler_1748_19-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation#cite_note-Euler_1748-19"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup></p></blockquote>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"20th_century">20th century<=
/h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DExponentiati=
on&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: 20th century">=
<span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span>=
</div>
<p>As calculation was mechanized, notation was adapted to numerical capacit=
y by conventions in exponential notation. For example <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Konrad_Zuse" title=3D"Konrad Zuse">Konrad Zuse</a> intr=
oduced <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Floating-point_arithmetic" =
title=3D"Floating-point arithmetic">floating-point arithmetic</a> in his 19=
38 computer Z1. One <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Register_(comp=
uter)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Register (computer)">register</a> con=
tained representation of leading digits, and a second contained representat=
ion of the exponent of 10. Earlier <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Leonardo_Torres_Quevedo" title=3D"Leonardo Torres Quevedo">Leonardo Torres=
 Quevedo</a> contributed <i>Essays on Automation</i> (1914) which had sugge=
sted the floating-point representation of numbers. The more flexible <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Decimal_floating-point" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Decimal floating-point">decimal floating-point</a> represent=
ation was introduced in 1946 with a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Bell_Laboratories" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Bell Laboratories">Bell=
 Laboratories</a> computer. Eventually educators and engineers adopted <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scientific_notation" title=3D"Scientif=
ic notation">scientific notation</a> of numbers, consistent with common ref=
erence to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Order_of_magnitude" titl=
e=3D"Order of magnitude">order of magnitude</a> in a <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Ratio_scale" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ratio scale"=
>ratio scale</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-20" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation#cite_note-20"><span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>For instance, in 1961 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
chool_Mathematics_Study_Group" title=3D"School Mathematics Study Group">Sch=
ool Mathematics Study Group</a> developed the notation in connection with u=
nits used in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metric_system" ti=
tle=3D"Metric system">metric system</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation#cite_note-=
21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation#cite_note-22"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Exponents also came to be used to describe <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Units_of_measurement" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Units =
of measurement">units of measurement</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Quantity_dimension" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Quantity dime=
nsion">quantity dimensions</a>. For instance, since <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Force" title=3D"Force">force</a> is mass times accelerati=
on, it is measured in kg m/sec<sup>2</sup>. Using M for mass, L for length,=
 and T for time, the expression M L T<sup>=E2=80=932</sup> is used in <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dimensional_analysis" title=3D"Dimensio=
nal analysis">dimensional analysis</a> to describe force.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-23" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponent=
iation#cite_note-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"=
cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation#cite_note-24"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Terminology">Terminology</h=
2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DExponentiation=
&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Terminology"><sp=
an>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></d=
iv>
<p>The expression <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i><sup>2</sup> =3D <i>b</i>=
 =C2=B7 <i>b</i></span> is called "the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Square_(algebra)" title=3D"Square (algebra)">square</a> of <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span>" or "<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span> s=
quared", because the area of a square with side-length <span class=3D"texht=
ml"><i>b</i></span> is <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i><sup>2</sup></span>.=
 (It is true that it could also be called "<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i>=
</span> to the second power", but "the square of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i=
>b</i></span>" and "<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span> squared" are mo=
re traditional)
</p><p>Similarly, the expression <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i><sup>3</su=
p> =3D <i>b</i> =C2=B7 <i>b</i> =C2=B7 <i>b</i></span> is called "the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cube_(algebra)" title=3D"Cube (algebra)=
">cube</a> of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span>" or "<span class=3D"t=
exhtml"><i>b</i></span> cubed", because the volume of a cube with side-leng=
th <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b</i></span> is <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>b<=
/i><sup>3</sup></span>.
</p><p>When an exponent is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Posit=
ive_integer" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Positive integer">positive inte=
ger</a>, that exponent indicates how many copies of the base are multiplied=
 together. For example, <span class=3D"texhtml">3<sup>5</sup> =3D 3 =C2=B7 =
3 =C2=B7 3 =C2=B7 3 =C2=B7 3 =3D 243</span>. The base <span class=3D"texhtm=
l">3</span> appears <span class=3D"texhtml">5</span> times in the multiplic=
ation, because the exponent is <span class=3D"texhtml">5</span>. Here, <spa=
n class=3D"texhtml">243</span> is the <i>5th power of 3</i>, or <i>3 raised=
 to the 5th power</i>.
</p><p>The word "raised" is usually omitted, and sometimes "power" as well,=
 so <span class=3D"texhtml">3<sup>5</sup></span> can be simply read "3 to t=
he 5th", or "3 to the 5".
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Integer_exponents">Integer =
exponents <span class=3D"anchor" id=3D"Integer"></span></h2><span class=3D"=
mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DExponentiation&amp;action=3Dedi=
t&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Integer exponents"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The exponentiation operation with integer exponents may be defined direc=
tly from elementary <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithmetic_ope=
ration" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Arithmetic operation">arithmetic ope=
rations</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Positive_exponents">Positiv=
e exponents</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Exponentiation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Po=
sitive exponents"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">]</span></span></div>
<p>The definition of the exponentiation as an iterated multiplication can b=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Formal_proof" title=3D"Formal pr=
oof">formalized</a> by using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathe=
matical_induction" title=3D"Mathematical induction">induction</a>,<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Exponentiation#cite_note-25"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and this definition can be used=
 as soon as one has an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Associativi=
ty" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Associativity">associative</a> multiplic=
ation:
</p><p>The base case is
</p>
<dl><dd><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span clas=
s=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
