</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/ff34617bed2fde3e9522f90496115935dca81c38" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.838ex; width:11.289ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle (x=
^{r})^{s}=3Dx^{rs}}"></span> to rational exponents.
</p><p>On the other hand, there are problems with the extension of these de=
finitions to bases that are not positive real numbers. For example, a negat=
ive real number has a real <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style=
:italic;">n</span>th root, which is negative, if <span class=3D"texhtml mva=
r" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Odd_number" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Odd number">odd</a>, a=
nd no real root if <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;=
">n</span> is even. In the latter case, whichever complex <span class=3D"te=
xhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>th root one chooses for <s=
pan class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-m=
ath-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmln=
s=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle x^{\frac=
 {1}{n}},}">
