ithm identities"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket=
">]</span></span></div>
<p>Some identities for powers and logarithms for positive real numbers will=
 fail for complex numbers, no matter how complex powers and complex logarit=
hms are defined <i>as single-valued functions</i>. For example:
</p>
<div><ul><li>The identity <span class=3D"texhtml">log(<i>b</i><sup><i>x</i>=
</sup>) =3D <i>x</i> =E2=8B=85 log=E2=80=89<i>b</i></span> holds whenever <=
span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span> is a posi=
tive real number and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">x</span> is a real number. But for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Principal_branch" title=3D"Principal branch">principal branch</a> =
of the complex logarithm one has
<p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"m=
we-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math=
 display=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"=
{\displaystyle \log((-i)^{2})=3D\log(-1)=3Di\pi \neq 2\log(-i)=3D2\log(e^{-=
i\pi /2})=3D2\,{\frac {-i\pi }{2}}=3D-i\pi }">
