f <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">x</span> (start=
ing indifferently from the exponent <span class=3D"texhtml">0</span> or <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml">1</span>).
</p><p>Order of elements play a fundamental role in <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Group_theory" title=3D"Group theory">group theory</a>. Fo=
r example, the order of an element in a finite group is always a divisor of=
 the number of elements of the group (the <i>order</i> of the group). The p=
ossible orders of group elements are important in the study of the structur=
e of a group (see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sylow_theorems" =
title=3D"Sylow theorems">Sylow theorems</a>), and in the <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classification_of_finite_simple_groups" title=3D"Cla=
ssification of finite simple groups">classification of finite simple groups=
</a>.
</p><p>Superscript notation is also used for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Conjugacy_class" title=3D"Conjugacy class">conjugation</a>; that=
 is, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i><sup><i>h</i></sup> =3D <i>h</i><sup>=
=E2=88=921</sup><i>gh</i></span>, where <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>g</i></s=
pan> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>h</i></span> are elements of a group. T=
his notation cannot be confused with exponentiation, since the superscript =
is not an integer. The motivation of this notation is that conjugation obey=
s some of the laws of exponentiation, namely <span class=3D"mwe-math-elemen=
t mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-m=
athml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/=
Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle (g^{h})^{k}=3Dg^{hk}}">
