n}=3D0}"></span> for some integer <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"fon=
t-style:italic;">n</span>. Such an element is said to be <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nilpotent" title=3D"Nilpotent">nilpotent</a>. In a <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Commutative_ring" title=3D"Commutat=
ive ring">commutative ring</a>, the nilpotent elements form an <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ideal_(ring_theory)" title=3D"Ideal (ring theo=
ry)">ideal</a>, called the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nilradi=
cal_of_a_ring" title=3D"Nilradical of a ring">nilradical</a> of the ring.
</p><p>If the nilradical is reduced to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
