<p>These examples are for discrete exponents of linear operators, but in ma=
ny circumstances it is also desirable to define powers of such operators wi=
th continuous exponents. This is the starting point of the mathematical the=
ory of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C0-semigroup" title=3D"C0-s=
emigroup">semigroups</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-44" class=3D"reference"><a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation#cite_note-44"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
 Just as computing matrix powers with discrete exponents solves discrete dy=
namical systems, so does computing matrix powers with continuous exponents =
solve systems with continuous dynamics. Examples include approaches to solv=
ing the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Heat_equation" title=3D"He=
at equation">heat equation</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sc=
hr%C3%B6dinger_equation" title=3D"Schr=C3=B6dinger equation">Schr=C3=B6ding=
er equation</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wave_equation" ti=
tle=3D"Wave equation">wave equation</a>, and other partial differential equ=
ations including a time evolution. The special case of exponentiating the d=
erivative operator to a non-integer power is called the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fractional_derivative" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"Fractional derivative">fractional derivative</a> which, together with the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fractional_integral" class=3D"mw-r=
edirect" title=3D"Fractional integral">fractional integral</a>, is one of t=
he basic operations of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fractio=
