<p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Field_(mathematics)" title=3D=
"Field (mathematics)">field</a> is an algebraic structure in which multipli=
cation, addition, subtraction, and division are defined and satisfy the pro=
perties that multiplication is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ass=
ociative" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Associative">associative</a> and e=
very nonzero element has a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multipl=
icative_inverse" title=3D"Multiplicative inverse">multiplicative inverse</a=
>. This implies that exponentiation with integer exponents is well-defined,=
 except for nonpositive powers of <span class=3D"texhtml">0</span>. Common =
examples are the field of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_=
number" title=3D"Complex number">complex numbers</a>, the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_number" title=3D"Real number">real numbers</a>=
 and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rational_number" title=3D=
"Rational number">rational numbers</a>, considered earlier in this article,=
 which are all <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infinite_set" title=
=3D"Infinite set">infinite</a>.
</p><p>A <i>finite field</i> is a field with a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Finite_set" title=3D"Finite set">finite number</a> of elements=
. This number of elements is either a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Prime_number" title=3D"Prime number">prime number</a> or a <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prime_power" title=3D"Prime power">prime power=
</a>; that is, it has the form <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-ele=
ment-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" st=
