<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Repeated_exponentiation">Re=
peated exponentiation</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-=
editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.ph=
p?title=3DExponentiation&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D45" title=3D"Edit =
section: Repeated exponentiation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tetration" title=3D=
"Tetration">Tetration</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hype=
roperation" title=3D"Hyperoperation">Hyperoperation</a></div>
<p>Just as exponentiation of natural numbers is motivated by repeated multi=
plication, it is possible to define an operation based on repeated exponent=
iation; this operation is sometimes called hyper-4 or tetration. Iterating =
tetration leads to another operation, and so on, a concept named hyperopera=
tion. This sequence of operations is expressed by the <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ackermann_function" title=3D"Ackermann function">Ackerm=
ann function</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knuth%27s_up-=
arrow_notation" title=3D"Knuth's up-arrow notation">Knuth's up-arrow notati=
on</a>. Just as exponentiation grows faster than multiplication, which is f=
aster-growing than addition, tetration is faster-growing than exponentiatio=
n. Evaluated at <span class=3D"texhtml">(3, 3)</span>, the functions additi=
on, multiplication, exponentiation, and tetration yield 6, 9, 27, and <span=
 class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"7012762559748498700=E2=99=A0"></=
span>7<span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">625</span><span style=3D"margin-le=
ft:.25em;">597</span><span style=3D"margin-left:.25em;">484</span><span sty=
le=3D"margin-left:.25em;">987</span></span> (<span class=3D"texhtml">=3D3<s=
up>27</sup> =3D 3<sup>3<sup>3</sup></sup> =3D <sup>3</sup>3</span>) respect=
ively.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Limits_of_powers">Limits of=
