t section: In programming languages"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw=
-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Programming_language" title=3D"=
Programming language">Programming languages</a> generally express exponenti=
ation either as an infix <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Operator_=
(computer_programming)" title=3D"Operator (computer programming)">operator<=
/a> or as a function application, as they do not support superscripts. The =
most common operator symbol for exponentiation is the <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caret" title=3D"Caret">caret</a> (<code>^</code>). The =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ASCII#1963" title=3D"ASCII">origin=
al version of ASCII</a> included an uparrow symbol (<code>=E2=86=91</code>)=
, intended for exponentiation, but this was <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Caret#History" title=3D"Caret">replaced by the caret</a> in 1967,=
 so the caret became usual in programming languages.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-51"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiatio=
n#cite_note-51"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup>
The notations include:
</p>
<ul><li><code>x ^ y</code>: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AWK" t=
itle=3D"AWK">AWK</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BASIC" title=
=3D"BASIC">BASIC</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J_programmin=
g_language" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"J programming language">J</a>, <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MATLAB" title=3D"MATLAB">MATLAB</a>=
, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wolfram_Language" title=3D"Wolfr=
am Language">Wolfram Language</a> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Wolfram_Mathematica" title=3D"Wolfram Mathematica">Mathematica</a>), <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/R_(programming_language)" title=3D"R (p=
rogramming language)">R</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Micro=
soft_Excel" title=3D"Microsoft Excel">Microsoft Excel</a>, <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytica_(software)" title=3D"Analytica (software=
)">Analytica</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TeX" title=3D"Te=
X">TeX</a> (and its derivatives), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
TI-BASIC" title=3D"TI-BASIC">TI-BASIC</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Bc_programming_language" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Bc program=
ming language">bc</a> (for integer exponents), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Haskell_(programming_language)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"Haskell (programming language)">Haskell</a> (for nonnegative integer expon=
ents), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lua_(programming_language)"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Lua (programming language)">Lua</a>, and mo=
st <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Computer_algebra_system" title=
=3D"Computer algebra system">computer algebra systems</a>.</li>
<li><code>x ** y</code>. The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fortr=
an" title=3D"Fortran">Fortran</a> character set did not include lowercase c=
haracters or punctuation symbols other than <code>+-*/()&amp;=3D.,'</code> =
and so used <code>**</code> for exponentiation<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Sayre_195=
6_52-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Expone=
ntiation#cite_note-Sayre_1956-52"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>50<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-53" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation#cite=
_note-53"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> (the initial version used <code>a xx b</code> instead=
.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Backus_1954_54-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation#cite_note-Backus_1954-54"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p>). Many other languages followed suit: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Ada_(programming_language)" title=3D"Ada (programming language)">Ada=
</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Z_shell" title=3D"Z shell">Z=
 shell</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KornShell" title=3D"Ko=
rnShell">KornShell</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bash_(Unix=
_shell)" title=3D"Bash (Unix shell)">Bash</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/COBOL" title=3D"COBOL">COBOL</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/CoffeeScript" title=3D"CoffeeScript">CoffeeScript</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fortran" title=3D"Fortran">Fortran</a>, <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FoxPro_2" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"FoxPro 2">FoxPro</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gnuplo=
t" title=3D"Gnuplot">Gnuplot</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Apache_Groovy" title=3D"Apache Groovy">Groovy</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/JavaScript" title=3D"JavaScript">JavaScript</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OCaml" title=3D"OCaml">OCaml</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Object_REXX" title=3D"Object REXX">ooRexx=
</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F_Sharp_(programming_languag=
e)" title=3D"F Sharp (programming language)">F#</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Perl" title=3D"Perl">Perl</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/PHP" title=3D"PHP">PHP</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/PL/I" title=3D"PL/I">PL/I</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Python_(programming_language)" title=3D"Python (programming language=
)">Python</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rexx" title=3D"Rexx=
">Rexx</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ruby_(programming_lang=
uage)" title=3D"Ruby (programming language)">Ruby</a>, <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/SAS_programming_language" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"SAS programming language">SAS</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Tcl" title=3D"Tcl">Tcl</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A=
BAP" title=3D"ABAP">ABAP</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Merc=
ury_(programming_language)" title=3D"Mercury (programming language)">Mercur=
y</a>, Haskell (for floating-point exponents), <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Turing_(programming_language)" title=3D"Turing (programming la=
nguage)">Turing</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/VHDL" tit=
le=3D"VHDL">VHDL</a>.</li>
<li><code>x =E2=86=91 y</code>: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Al=
gol_programming_language" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Algol programming =
language">Algol Reference language</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Commodore_BASIC" title=3D"Commodore BASIC">Commodore BASIC</a>, <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TRS-80_Level_II_BASIC" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"TRS-80 Level II BASIC">TRS-80 Level II/III BASIC</a>.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-InfoWorld_1982_55-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation#cite_note-InfoWorld_1982-55"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-80Micro_1983_56-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation#cite_note-80Micro_1983-56"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up></li>
<li><code>x ^^ y</code>: Haskell (for fractional base, integer exponents), =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/D_(programming_language)" title=3D=
"D (programming language)">D</a>.</li>
<li><code>x=E2=8B=86y</code>: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/APL_=
(programming_language)" title=3D"APL (programming language)">APL</a>.</li><=
/ul>
<p>In most programming languages with an infix exponentiation operator, it =
is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Operator_associativity" title=
=3D"Operator associativity">right-associative</a>, that is, <code>a^b^c</co=
de> is interpreted as <code>a^(b^c)</code>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-57" class=3D=
"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Exponentiation#cite_no=
te-57"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>55<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup> This is because <code>(a^b)^c</code> is equal to <code>a=
^(b*c)</code> and thus not as useful. In some languages, it is left-associa=
tive, notably in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algol" title=3D"A=
lgol">Algol</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MATLAB" title=3D"=
MATLAB">MATLAB</a>, and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Micros=
oft_Office_Excel" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Microsoft Office Excel">Mi=
crosoft Excel</a> formula language.
</p><p>Other programming languages use functional notation:
</p>
<ul><li><code>(expt x y)</code>: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C=
ommon_Lisp" title=3D"Common Lisp">Common Lisp</a>.</li>
<li><code>pown x y</code>: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F_Sharp=
_(programming_language)" title=3D"F Sharp (programming language)">F#</a> (f=
or integer base, integer exponent).</li></ul>
<p>Still others only provide exponentiation as part of standard <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Library_(computing)" title=3D"Library (comput=
ing)">libraries</a>:
</p>
<ul><li><code>pow(x, y)</code>: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C_=
(programming_language)" title=3D"C (programming language)">C</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C%2B%2B" title=3D"C++">C++</a> (in <code>=
math</code> library).</li>
<li><code>Math.Pow(x, y)</code>: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/C=
_Sharp_(programming_language)" title=3D"C Sharp (programming language)">C#<=
/a>.</li>
<li><code>math:pow(X, Y)</code>: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E=
rlang_(programming_language)" title=3D"Erlang (programming language)">Erlan=
g</a>.</li>
<li><code>Math.pow(x, y)</code>: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J=
ava_(programming_language)" title=3D"Java (programming language)">Java</a>.=
</li>
<li><code>[Math]::Pow(x, y)</code>: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/PowerShell" title=3D"PowerShell">PowerShell</a>.</li></ul>
<p>In some <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Type_system" title=3D"T=
ype system">statically typed</a> languages that prioritize <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Type_safety" title=3D"Type safety">type safety</a>=
 such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rust_(programming_languag=
e)" title=3D"Rust (programming language)">Rust</a>, exponentiation is perfo=
rmed via a multitude of methods:
</p>
<ul><li><code>x.pow(y)</code> for <code>x</code> and <code>y</code> as inte=
gers</li>
<li><code>x.powf(y)</code> for <code>x</code> and <code>y</code> as floatin=
g-point numbers</li>
<li><code>x.powi(y)</code> for <code>x</code> as a float and <code>y</code>=
 as an integer</li></ul>
